[5] California (Napa County)
Date: Fri 20 Jun 2014
Source: Napa Valley Register [edited]
http://napavalleyregister.com/news/local/st-helena-hospital-limits-visits-due-to-pertussis-spike/article_8f550f4a-b0d9-5c2c-a883-e6f786ed9f30.html


St Helena Hospital is curbing visits to its maternity section due to California's declaration of a whooping cough epidemic, the medical center announced Fri 20 Jun 2014. No visitors with coughing, runny nose, fever, or similar symptoms will be admitted to the family birthing center, according to Karen Phillips, infection prevention specialist at the hospital. In addition, children under 18 -- including siblings of newborns -- can enter only with proof of immunization for the bacterial disease, also called pertussis.

The restrictions at St Helena Hospital were issued following similar visiting curbs issued Tue 17 Jun 2014, at Queen of the Valley Medical Center in Napa.

Since 1 Jan 2014, confirmed and suspected cases of pertussis in Napa County already are up 7-fold, to 91, from the number reported for all of 2013. Whooping cough reports in California have totaled more than 3400 in 2014, the most in 4 years, with 2 deaths.

